Text.Value: They likely died as vampire spawn. Which is probably a mercy, honestly.
Until then, go in peace. And thank you.
Perhaps there was something to that. A kindness I would not have credited you with.
What? You treacherous little shit - I'll kill you all!
Oh I don't know - this might be the perfect place for them to die.
You lie to cover your sins? To blame the vampire for your choices?
I can't. There has to be another way.
And you don't know the scar you've left in our tribe, spawn.
Hold there, spawn.
Oh, I wasn't holding out for an invitation.
Look at the hate in their eyes. They won't ever stop hunting me.
Perhaps, but the choice should still have been ours. You have taken them from us twice now.
Believe me when I say it was for the best. The pain from the hunger alone - there's nothing like it.
I've visited enough pain on your people. The least I could do was spare you that.
Farewell. For good, I hope.
Spawn? I am the Vampire Ascendant, Gur. And I thought I was done with your wretched little tribe.
I admit, I had my doubts.
Thank you for what you have done - slaying Cazador was a great justice. As for the rest... well, time will tell.
A fool I was, to ever hope a beast like you could be saved.
But you have rid this land of your old master, so... consider things settled between us.
One blood-sucking beast replaced with another. Our children sacrificed to birth a monster.
There is not.
Kill them. Kill them all!

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Over her shoulder, to the other hunters standing behind her.

Text.Value: And our children? What of their fate?
You'll find them in the Underdark, although you may not like what you find.
Well that's backhanded as compliments come. Though I'll take it if it means you're done trying to kill me.
You're right, Astarion has to be stopped.
My dear, I wouldn't want it any other way.
So I can see from all your heavily-armed friends. You didn't think I could resist completing the ritual, did you?
We will not hunt you, but you will never be welcome around our fire.
Oh please, there's no need for such language. I promised you Cazador's death and I more than delivered.
We gave you a choice and you chose power. As your kind always does.
As for you, you have my people's thanks. I know you face trials ahead - we will stand with you as best we can.
I - I'm sorry. We were too late. Cazador had already turned them.
This is... difficult news. We will need to decide what it means.
I - I don't know for sure, but Cazador turned everyone we brought him. I can only assume that included your children.
They died as vampire spawn. It was the only mercy we could give them.
Killing children makes for a strange kind of mercy. Although given what they'd become...
But I still have hope for you - that you will make a better choice.
Say nothing.
They - they survived?
They were innocents. To kill them would have been an even greater crime.
I need Astarion strong to save the city. This is the lesser evil, I promise.
Your companion attacked us in the night and stole our children. Then his master decimated what was left of the tribe.
I have. I've stolen your last chance to see them, and I'd do it again in a heartbeat.
And what do we find when we arrive?

EditorData.NodeContext: This line could be followed by an aggressive line ("one blood-sucking beast replaced with another") or an impressed line ("you killed not only Cazador, but also his wretched creations.") so it needs to be tonally neutral

Text.Value: No, there's no working with the likes of them. Look at the hate in their eyes.
However twisted, there is a logic there... Very well.
A monster. A truly wretched monster.
You think that's what you wanted, but you don't know the hunger. You don't know what it turns us into.
You killed one vampire, but released seven thousand of his spawn? Have you lost all sense?
Thank you. And for what it's worth - I'm sorry. I wish I could return the ones taken from you.
We're not done. Not even close.
I had hoped to avoid this path. I had hoped you would choose the better road.
I had no choice. As you 'monster hunters' well know.
We searched half the Sword Coast for you, hoping you could help us destroy him, only to track you right back here.
You'll find them sealed in the cells below the palace. Although you might not like what you find.
No. I stand with him.
Walk away, Ulma. Your tribe doesn't need to die here.
There is no greater or lesser, there is only evil. And it stands before me.
I even killed a few thousand spawn while I was at it - you should be thanking me for saving you the trouble.
I never dreamt a spawn could find redemption, but - yes. You will never be hunted again.
But if you do decide to go hunting them, know they include your children.
My name's Ulma, my people are monster hunters. Those of us that remain, that is.
Then you are as much a monster as he.
So when you destroyed the spawn, you killed them too?
Mercy? They were our children - mercy would have been giving us a chance to say goodbye. To decide their fate ourselves.
You can't blame a spawn for the sins of his master. Any good monster hunter should know that.
And worse, you thought we would not know? You are hardly better than the beast you slew.
Cazador turned everyone we brought him into spawn. I can only assume your children were somewhere in those wretched cells.
Because anything else would mean sending you down into the dark. It'd mean showing you the hunger in your babes' eyes and leaving you with that terrible, final decision.
But we did slay him, so... how about we call it even?
They died long before we arrived. Trust me, they were not the children you knew.
You're - the Gur tribe? I thought I was done with you people.
Cazador is destroyed and his plans ruined. I was not sure you could do it.
Will you stand against evil. Will you help us destroy this monster?
But thanks to you, a monster that will never rear its head again. You have our thanks.
That depends on how you define 'survived', really, but they are free. They're making their way into the Underdark as we speak.
But where are our children? What of their fate?
That being said, slaying Cazador was a great justice. You have our thanks, now and forever.
Please, there's no need for such language. You wanted Cazador dead and now he is.
You gave them peace. There was nothing more we could ask of you.
You are free - never again will you be hunted by my people.
We were too late. Cazador killed them.
You killed not only Cazador, but also his wretched creations. I expected less.
We don't have to fight. We can work together.
You'll probably find them in the cells below the palace. Although you won't like what you find.
True. So imagine my surprise when I heard you'd fled. Heard you were a rogue spawn, free from Cazador's control.

Synopsis: Dialog with the Gur Leader after you defeated Cazador
